description:
## Description
The `GetMap` function in `pkg/resource/metadata.go` has a type assertion bug that prevents metadata from being loaded correctly from YAML frontmatter.

## Problem
When YAML unmarshals nested maps, they are unmarshaled as `Frontmatter` type (which is `map[string]interface{}`), but the `GetMap` function tries to assert to `map[string]interface{}` which fails the type check because `Frontmatter` is a named type.

## Evidence
```go
// This fails because val is of type Frontmatter, not map[string]interface{}
if m, ok := val.(map[string]interface{}); ok {
    // Never reached
}
```

## Impact
- Metadata fields are not loaded when reading agent/skill/command resources
- Round-trip write/read of metadata fails silently
- Skills and agents lose metadata after write/load cycle

## Reproduction
See test in /tmp/test_getmap.go or /tmp/test_metadata.go

## Fix
Change the type assertion in GetMap to handle both types:
```go
func (f Frontmatter) GetMap(key string) map[string]string {
    result := make(map[string]string)
    if val, ok := f[key]; ok {
        // Try direct map[string]interface{} first
        if m, ok := val.(map[string]interface{}); ok {
            for k, v := range m {
                if str, ok := v.(string); ok {
                    result[k] = str
                }
            }
        } else if m, ok := val.(Frontmatter); ok {
            // Also handle nested Frontmatter type
            for k, v := range m {
                if str, ok := v.(string); ok {
                    result[k] = str
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return result
}
```

## Affected Files
- `pkg/resource/metadata.go` - GetMap function
- `pkg/resource/agent.go` - LoadAgent uses GetMap for metadata
- `pkg/resource/skill.go` - LoadSkill uses GetMap for metadata  
- `pkg/resource/command.go` - LoadCommand uses GetMap for metadata (if applicable)

## Tests Affected
- Agent tests skip metadata verification (noted in comments)
- Skill tests don't verify metadata loading
- Command tests may have same issue

## Out of Scope
This is a pre-existing bug discovered while working on ai-config-manager-494 (agent unit tests). It should be fixed separately.

## Description
Create integration tests to verify bulk import functionality works end-to-end for both plugin and Claude folder imports.

## Instructions
1. Create `test/bulk_import_test.go` file
2. Test scenarios:
   - Import from valid plugin structure
   - Import from valid Claude folder
   - Import with conflicts (force, skip, fail)
   - Import with dry-run mode
   - Import from invalid paths (error handling)
3. Test helpers needed:
   - setupTestPlugin(tmpDir) - creates test plugin structure
   - setupTestClaudeFolder(tmpDir) - creates test .claude/ structure
   - verifyImportResult(result, expectedCounts) - validates results
4. Test structure:
   ```go
   func TestPluginImport(t *testing.T) {
       // Create temp plugin with commands and skills
       // Run import
       // Verify resources in repo
       // Check summary output
   }

   func TestClaudeImport(t *testing.T) {
       // Create temp .claude/ folder
       // Run import
       // Verify resources in repo
   }

   func TestBulkImportConflicts(t *testing.T) {
       // Add resource first
       // Import same resource with different flags
       // Verify behavior (force, skip, fail)
   }
   ```

## Files to Create
- test/bulk_import_test.go - Integration tests

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Tests cover plugin import scenarios
- [ ] Tests cover Claude folder import scenarios
- [ ] Tests verify conflict handling (force, skip, fail)
- [ ] Tests verify dry-run mode
- [ ] Tests verify error handling
- [ ] All tests pass: `make integration-test`
- [ ] Tests follow existing integration test patterns

## Dependencies
- Requires: add plugin command (ai-config-manager-222)
- Requires: add claude command (ai-config-manager-9r7)

## Notes
- Use t.TempDir() for test directories
- Reference test/integration_test.go for patterns
- Test both happy path and error cases
